<FONT CLASS="ArticleSource"><BIG>Absor:</BIG></FONT> 
<FONT CLASS="ArticleHead"><BIG>Whistling in the Dark</BIG></FONT>
<FONT CLASS="ArticleAuthorLight">&nbsp;filed by </FONT><FONT CLASS="ArticleAuthor">Kohath</FONT>
<DIV ALIGN=RIGHT>
<FONT CLASS=ArticleTime>07/25/2001 09:01 AM CDT</FONT>
<DIV ALIGN=LEFT>
<FONT CLASS=ArticleText>
<b>Sadim wrote:</b><br><i>I thought that all the exp penalties where taken out of the game a couple of months ago to encourage grouping. Or was it just the class exp penalties?<p>thank you</i><p><b>The class penalties were eliminated. The racial penalties remain. The benefits for playing certain races still exist.<p>But...</b><p><i>&quot;Races that can see in the dark pay an experience penalty for that ability.&quot;<p>Unless something has changed unannounced, this isn't true.<p>Humans don't have any experience benefit over wood/high elves with infravision, nor dark elves with ultravision.<p>The only races with experience penalties are the big races (which get Slam) and Iksar (which have extra regeneration and an AC bonus).<p>In fact, one race levels faster than humans, the halflings, and they have infravision!<p>--<br>Kiatha Kittenpaw<br>Feir`Dal Ranger<br>The Nameless</i><p><b>The only thing I can figure is that someone slipped something into my coffee...<p>You're correct. I'm certain that visual ability had an effect on the decision making process for racial penalties. But obviously just having better vision wasn't enough of a reason to get one.<p>I stand by the immersiveness concept. I've played the much beleaguered Erudite in Tox. It's absolutely disconcerting to get lost out there when you can't see.<p>Antsy wrote:</b><p><i>Wood elves and high elves have an experience penalty compared to barbarians Erudites? Are you sure?<p>And why would blind old Erud settle in some place as dark as Toxxulia? (I'm sure you are aware that Erudite characters all move at an early age because they as so poorly adapted to their newbie zone.)<p>PS: the category section is a nice addition to the form here, but it shouldn't be necessary when responding to an existing post should it?</i><p><b>Not all Erudites leave their homelands at early ages.<p>Erud didn't have a lot of options. I imagine that if he could have relocated to Hawaii or someplace similar, he would have. <p>No, there really shouldn't be categories when responding to existing posts. That's there because I failed to communicate properly. We're working on fixing that this week.</b><p><i>Absor,<p>For one reason or another, all of my characters that I play significantly are of the night-blind races. I have no problem with there being places where I will be virtually unable to see without a light source. However, in most outdoor zones, lightsources seem to do little to help me see, even Greater lightstones. A prime example of this is making the run through Kithicor at night. Often times, I am completely unable to see even the wall of the zone while I run along it. <p>I believe that this is a Graphics engine problem, not one that's intented. I seem to remember a post long, long ago where it was explained that polygons that were larger than the effective area of a light source would not be illuminated, even if the player was standing right on top of them. This doesn't seem to be a problem in dungeons, as the space is more confined, and most of the polygons making up the walls and ceiling are small. It is however, rather annoying for my blind characters when I try and run along paths in Greater faydark, and I can't even see the ground most of the time with a Greater lightstone.<p>I don't know if this problem would go away with one of the latest graphics cards, but mine should not be that underpowered. [ATI Rage Fury - 32MB]<p>Thanks for your time,<br>Olav Skulcrusher, Barbarian Champion<br>Balthozzar, Human Wizard<br>Falcon's Pride<br>The Nameless</i><p><b>The way I understand it, it's not the video card as much as the game engine. It's certainly not intended, but there are instances where light doesn't reflect off surfaces properly, leaving darkness where there probably should be light. You shouldn't see that on Luclin at all, but there's little we can to do correct it in the old world.<p>Alan</b><p>In other words: <p>It's just dark, OK?  No reason for it.  Some people get dark, some people get light.  Abashi knew how to answer these types of questions:<p>&quot;Shut up RIGHT NOW or we'll make it dark for everyone all the time!  Where's my nerf bat?  It's not really dark at all, it's just a perception.  It's actually blindingly bright.  Are you sure your monitor is turned on?&quot;
</FONT>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
